Data Visualization

from requests import get
import numpy as np 
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

ches = pd.read_csv('https://www.chesdata.eu/s/CHES_2024_final_v2.csv')

Visualization

Visualization Goals

  • We want to summarize the distribution of variables, describe their central tendency, or show how they relate to each other.

  • When youâre exploring your own data, you donât have to worry too much about formatting

  • When youâre using a visual to communicate something, clarity is key.

Minimum things you need for a visualization

For final projects (and beyond)

  • Graphs or tables should always have descriptive labels (not just default variable names like âpid3_catâ) and a title or caption. Readers shouldnât need a lot of background knowledge to interpret your graphs.

  • Avoid âover-plottingâ or cases where data or labels overlap with each other

  • You should include interpretation in the text alongside your plot or graph.

Plotting Packages

Weâll primarily use:

  • Pandas + Matplotlib: this will be our default for most plotting. Pandas makes some basic plotting operations very easy, but weâll still need to use Matplot for some finer detail.

  • Seaborn: Includes some easy-to-use default settings that can make more complicated plots with a little less code.

  • Plotly (and Bokeh, time permitting) are packages for creating interactive visualizations that can be embedded in a Jupyter notebook.

Figures and axes

When working matplotlib figures, weâll usually want to start with something like fig, axes = plt.subplots() and end with plt.show()

This creates an empty space and allows us to adjust things like the title or x-axis labels after weâve created the plot.

You donât have to do this every time, its primarily useful when you are making plots for presentation purposes.

fig, axes = plt.subplots()

axes.set_title("Empty plot")

plt.show()

Basic Plot types (1 variable)

Histogram

Histograms show the distribution of a single continuous variable.

Split data into âbinsâ and then count observations in each bin:

Histogram

Example:

fig, axes = plt.subplots()
ches['lrecon'].hist(ax=axes)
axes.set_title("Left-Right Scores for European Parties in 2024")
axes.set_xlabel("lrecon")
axes.set_ylabel('count')
plt.show()

Histogram

Usually, the default setting works here, but you can adjust the number of bins up or down to change the sizing:

fig, axes = plt.subplots()
ches['lrecon'].hist(bins=20, ax=axes)
axes.set_title("Left-Right Scores for European Parties in 2024")
axes.set_xlabel("lrecon")
axes.set_ylabel('count')
plt.show()

Histogram

We can also set grid=False to remove the grid lines and adjust the size (along with several other options documented here)

fig, axes = plt.subplots( figsize = (10, 5))

ches['lrecon'].hist(bins = 20, grid=False, ax=axes)
axes.set_title("Left-Right Scores for European Parties in 2024")
axes.set_xlabel("lrecon")
axes.set_ylabel('count')
plt.show()

Density plot

Kernel density plots are like a âsmoothâ version of a histogram.

fig, axes = plt.subplots()
ches['lrecon'].plot.density(ax=axes)
axes.set_title("Left-Right Scores for European Parties in 2024")
plt.show()

Density plot

  • One disadvantage relative to a histogram is that the Y-axis is not readily interpretable
fig, axes = plt.subplots()

ches['lrecon'].plot.density(ax=axes)
axes.set_title("Left-Right Scores for European Parties in 2024")
plt.show()

Density plot

  • One disadvantage relative to a histogram is that the Y-axis is not readily interpretable

  • One advantage is that it can be easier to show multiple density plots together

fig, axes = plt.subplots()


ches[['lrecon', 'galtan']].plot.density(ax=axes)
axes.set_title("Left-Right Scores and GAL-TAN scores for European Parties in 2024")
plt.show()

Bar plot

One variable bar plots will give the count of each unique value in a column.

Most often, weâll be using the output from an aggregation function like value_counts first, then plotting the resulting frequency table.

Bar plot example

fig, axes = plt.subplots()
ches.family.value_counts().plot.bar(ax=axes)
axes.set_xlabel("Party Family")
plt.show()

Bar plot

barh will generate a horizontal barplot

fig, axes = plt.subplots()
ches.family.value_counts().plot.barh(ax=axes)
axes.set_xlabel("Party Family")
plt.show()

Bar plot

And we can do things like adjust the color

fig, axes = plt.subplots()
ches.family.value_counts().plot.barh(color='#E03A3E', ax=axes)
axes.set_xlabel("Party Family")
plt.show()

Pie charts

Finally, pie charts can be useful for giving the proportion of results belonging to each group (but in many cases a bar chart may convey this information more clearly)

fig, axes = plt.subplots(figsize=(5,5))
ches.family.value_counts(normalize='index').plot.pie(autopct='%.1f%%', ax=axes)
axes.set_title('Party Families')
plt.show()

Basic Plot types (2 or more variables)

Boxplots

Boxplots will give a five number summary (minimum, maximum, 25th, 50th, and 75th percentiles) of a continuous variable.

They can work to describe a single variable, but theyâre most useful for examining the relationship between a category and a numeric variable.

Boxplots Example

fig, axes = plt.subplots()
ches.boxplot(by='family', column='people_v_elite', figsize=(10,5), grid=False, ax=axes)
axes.set_xlabel("Party Family")
axes.set_ylabel("People vs. Elites rhetoric")
axes.set_title("Populism for European parties in 2024")
plt.show()

Bar charts (2-way)

2-way bar charts will work best for visualizing a 2-way crosstab, or showing the average across values of a categorical variable.

Bar charts (2-way) Example

fig, axes = plt.subplots()
ches.pivot_table(index='family', values='lrecon').plot.bar(ax=axes)
axes.set_xlabel("Party Family")
axes.set_ylabel("Average Left-Right Econ position")
Text(0, 0.5, 'Average Left-Right Econ position')

Scatter plots

Scatter plots will work best when both variables are continuous.

Be careful about overplotting: if there are only a small number of response categories, a scatter plot may give you weird looking results because multiple points end up right on top of each other.

Scatter plot example

fig, axes = plt.subplots()
ches.plot.scatter(x='lrecon', y='galtan', ax=axes)
axes.set_xlabel("Left-Right")
axes.set_ylabel("GAL-TAN")
plt.show()

Multiple plots

Matplot makes it relatively easy to combine multiple plots into the same figure. Youâll just need to specify the number of rows and columns for your figure, and then assign a plot to each axis using an index.

Multiple plots example

fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 1, sharex=True, sharey=True, figsize=(10,10))
ches.plot.scatter(x='lrecon', y='galtan', ax=axes[0])
ches.plot.scatter(x='lrecon', y='immigrate_policy', ax=axes[1])
ches.plot.scatter(x='lrecon', y='environment', ax=axes[2])

axes[0].set_title("multiple scatter plots")

plt.show()
